**Installing Arduino**  
To begin, you must have the application Arduino installed on your pc or laptop. To install the application visit [Arduino](https://www.arduino.cc/en/software).  
![Installing Arduino](images/installing_arduino1.JPG)

             Once you reach the download page, select the  
             download option that works for your computer.   
  If you are using Windows, **DO NOT** download it as   
  a zip file. Select either the **Windows 64 Bit App** or  
  **Windows installer**. 

 Once the download is complete, a zip file may appear on your computer if you are using a Mac  
or in the downloads folder if you are on Windows (most likely found in the Downloads folder or Desktop) 

On Mac \- Open the zip file and the Arduino application should appear then drag it into the Applications Folder

On Windows \- Launch either the 64 Bits Application or the MSI Installer continue with the install

---

**Arduino Environment**

Now that the Arduino application has been successfully installed, open the application. The Arduino IDE should look ← something like this.

← This is where the code is written to run Arduino programs.

← Any error messages will appear   
here once you run your code. 

---

**Installing Adafruit Packages and Libraries**

Before you can run any programs on the Arduino you will need to install a few packages and libraries. Without these installations, your Arduino will not be able to run any programs. 

**This first installation is necessary for the Arduino application to have access to some of the Adafruit libraries that you will need.** 

To install this package you need to copy this link   **↓**

### **https://adafruit.github.io/arduino-board-index/package\_adafruit\_index.json**

Once the link has been copied, go to the Arduino application on your laptop/pc and click on Arduino \-\>Settings

Paste the link you copied in “Additional Boards Manager URLs”

Click “Ok” and close the Arduino Application

Next, you will need to go to Tools \-\> Board \-\> Boards Manager

   

 

Now that you are done downloading the necessary boards on Boards Manager, close the Boards Manager window. 

In the search bar type “Wifi 101” and install the library called “Wifi 101”

![Installing Arduino](images/installing_arduino2.JPG)

Repeat this step with the following libraries (For libraries that require other libraries to be installed, click install all when prompted):

* Adafruit Sleepy Dog   
* SparkFun SCD4X Arduino Library  
* Adafruit GFX  
* Adafruit SSD1306  
* Adafruit BME280  
* Adafruit SH110X  
* Adafruit BusIO  
* Sensirion I2C SEN5X  
* flashstorage  
* WIFI 101  
    
* Honeywell TruStability SPI  
  * Download from [Github](https://github.com/huilab/HoneywellTruStabilitySPI)  
  * In Arduino IDE Select Sketch, then Include Library and click on add Zip Library then open the ZIP folder that you have just downloaded.

* RTClib.h  
  * Download from [Github](https://github.com/adafruit/RTClib)  
  * In Arduino IDE Select Sketch, then Include Library and click on add Zip Library then open the ZIP folder that you have just downloaded.

    

**Now you are done\!**   
Below are some additional instructions.  
---

**Connecting Your Arduino \- Compiling and Uploading**

* Plug in your Arduino to your laptop using a Micro-USB Cable to your computer. (If you do not have a USB port on your computer you will need a adapter)  
    
    
    
    
    
    
    
    
    
    
    
    
* Launch Arduino IDE and select the correct port with the dropdown menu  
    
    
    
    
* When you have the correct port selected and you are ready to Compile code to your Arduino. First compile the code to check for any errors beforehand.


* When there are no errors present in under output. You can now upload the code to your Arduino




---

**Running Blink example: testing connections (Computer with Arduino)**

Now that you have all the libraries downloaded, you can test the connection between the Sensor and your computer. 

* Head to File \> Examples \> Basics \> Blink to pull up the blink code that can be used to test if the sensor is connected to your computer (Will need a adaptor to connect)  and can have code uploaded to it  
  * Upload the code and look at the sensor when the code finish uploading to check it the light is blinking
